The paper presents a technique for inferring causal features in a system of multiple agents without requiring knowledge of the environment. This involves using Gaussian processes to jointly infer a spatio-temporal vector field and vector calculus operations on that field. The paper also evaluates the approach using both synthetic and real-world GPS data. Based on this, the most likely sub-categories are cs.AI (artificial intelligence) and cs.LG (machine learning), as the paper involves probabilistic inference and learning from data. The other likely sub-categories are cs.SI (social and information networks), cs.SY (systems and control), and cs.RO (robotics), as the paper deals with multiple agents and their dynamics in a non-stationary environment.
